What the Post Shows
The post contains a high-quality animation of hydrogen atom wavefunctions (electron probability clouds) evolving and transitioning between different quantum states.
It visualizes how the probability density of the electron changes shape as it moves between energy levels. The animation is labeled with quantum numbers (n, l, m) and shows the electron cloud dynamically reshaping rather than staying in fixed, static “orbitals.”
The post’s main point is educational: These are not fixed paths or rigid shells — they are time-evolving probability distributions.
Scientific Context
This is a visualization of solutions to the Schrödinger equation for the hydrogen atom. Key points:
The shapes represent |ψ|² (the probability density of finding the electron at a given point in space).
Different combinations of quantum numbers (n = energy level, l = orbital shape, m = orientation) produce different geometric probability clouds (spherical, dumbbell, cloverleaf, etc.).
When the electron transitions between states (by absorbing or emitting a photon), the wavefunction evolves smoothly from one probability distribution to another.
The animation effectively shows the dynamic nature of quantum states, which is more accurate than the static orbital diagrams taught in most chemistry classes.
